ecause everyone already pays taxes) and therefore would do little to alleviate the issues.  2. Parent's who send their students to private schools will not necessarily be able to fix the problems with public schools. Public schools with the biggest problems are often located in districts where very few students attend private schools, like wise, some of the best private schools already exist in distracts were many students do attend private schools (economics has a lot to do with this, and activism has very little to do with it). 3. To say that parent's who prioritize their child's education are &quot;bad&quot; is a ridiculous statement. The failing of the public school system has nothing to do with where students are attending (or where parents send their students) and everything to do with our nations inability to address our economic disparities and our governments complete lack of understanding as it pertains to pedagogy and education practices.  Articles like these lower of the level of the national discourse on a very important issue and give less reasoned and educated individuals inflammatory and unsupported talking points. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1446" language="en" documentId="3377" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Bopbie" date="Aug 29, 2013 7:18PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="10" thumbsDown="0" origId="3377" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1446"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>